Sheet 7: Description
Function Input Description Output
P1 Handwheel torque Handwheel torque data from the sensor The sensed handwheel torque data is processed and converted to engineering units Processed handwheel torque data
P2 Pinion angle Handwheel position data; Motor angle data The data is processed and converted to engineering units to provide the pinion angle Pinion angle data
P3 Motor angle Data from the motor angle sensor (Part of motor sensong sub-system) The data is processed and converted into engineering units to provide the motor angle Motor angle data
P4 Motor velocity Data from the motor angle sensor (Part of motor sensong sub-system) Processing of the data to estimate the motor velocity Estimated motor velocity data
P5 Temperature ECU temperature data; Ambient temperature data Process the ECU temperature data and the ambient temperature data and provide an estimate for the system temperature Estimated system temperature value
P6 Motor current Data from the motor current monitoring component Data is processed and converted to corresponding engineering units Motor current value
P7 Vehicle communications Data from the vehicle ECU (Vehicle Signals); Data from the steering system (System Signals) Communicate with the vehicle ECU. That is send system signals and receive vehicle signals as required Two way communication between the system and the vehicle is established
P8 Supply voltage Vehicle power supply Receive, distribute and regulate (if required) the vehicle power supply throughout the system where required; Monitor the vehicle power supply and determine the battery voltage, bridge voltage Power supply received, distributed and regulated (if necessary) within the system; Battery voltage, bridge voltage
P9 Calculate torque overlay command Handwheel torque data; Pinion angle data; Vehicle signals Based on vehicle assist commands and for executing active return feature, calculate a torque overlay command Motor torque command overlay; Handwheel torque overlay
P10 Calculate torque command modifiers Handwheel torque data; Pinion angle data; Estimated motor velocity data; Vehicle signals Based on the input, determine the forces (external and internal) acting on the steering system which needs to be compensated and calculate modifiers for the torque command to achieve this compensation Motor torque command modifier
P11 Calculate motor torque command limit Motor current value; Battery voltage data; Bridge voltage data; Estimated system temperature value Check for power supply & system temperature and calculate limits for the motor torque command to protect the system Motor torque command limit; Motor torque command scalar
P12 Calculate motor torque command Motor torque command overlay; Handwheel torque overlay; Motor torque command modifier; Motor torque command limit From the torque command overlays, modifiers and limits, calculate the motor torque command with the required motor torque value to provide intended assist Motor torque command
P13 Calculate motor voltage command Motor torque command Interpret the motor torque command in terms of the motor characteristics and come up with a motor voltage command Motor voltage command
P14 Generate motor voltage Motor voltage command Generate motor voltage as per the motor voltage command Motor voltage
P15 Provide motor torque Motor voltage Operate the motor, generate torque and provide the generated torque as assistance Provided motor torque (Net assist output)
S1 Calibrations - - -
S2 Security - - -
S3 Diagnostics - Conduct a system level diagnostics to determine the health of the system and in turn help determint the state in which the system should operate System health determined
S4 States and Modes - The system behaviour is captured as system states and modes System states and modes, their transitions and conditions for transitions are defined
S5 Manufacturing services - - -
S6 Diagnostic services - - -





P1.1 Handwheel torque measurement Handwheel torque signal from the driver sensor The handwheel torque signal is received and measured by the electric hardware Received and measured handwheel torque signal
P1.2 Handwheel torque calculation and diagnostics Received and measured handwheel torque signal The handwheel torque signal is converted to engineering units and it is checked for its validity Handwheel torque data; Handwheel torque data validity information
P2.1 Pinion angle measurement Handwheel position signal from the handwheel position sensor The pinion angle signal is received and measured by the electric hardware Received and measured pinion angle signal
P2.2 Pinion angle calculation Received and measured pinion angle signal The pinion angle signal is converted to engineering units Pinion angle data
P3.1 Sense motor angle - Motor angle is sensed by means of a motor angle sensor Motor angle signal; Motor turns count
P3.2 Motor angle measurement Motor angle signal; Motor turns count The motor angle signal is received and measured by the electric hardware Received and measured motor angle signal
P3.3 Motor angle calculations and diagnostics Received and measured motor angle signal The motor angle signal is converted to engineering units and it is checked for its validity Motor angle data; Motor angle data validity information
P4.1 Provide motor velocity estimation Motor angle data The motor velocity is estimated by the rate of change of the sensed, measured and calculated motor angle data Motor velocity estimation data
P5.1 Temperature measurement Temperature of the control module board The temperature of the control module board is measured by means of a thermistor; The measured temperature value is calculated to come up with the ECU temperature data ECU temperature
P5.2 Temperature calculation ECU temperature The motor temperature and the mechanical actuator temperature are estimated from the measured and calculated ECU temperature data Mechanical actuator temperature estimation; Motor temperature estimation
P6.1 Motor current measurement - The motor current is meaured by means of a measuring component in the electric hardware Measured motor current signal
P6.2 Motor current arbitration and diagnostics Measured motor current signal The measured motor current signal is converted to engineering units and it is checked for its validity Motor current data; Motor current data validity information
P15.1 Generate motor torque Generated motor voltage The electric motor generates the motor torque based on the voltage supplied to it Generated motor torque which acts as the assistance to the driver's steering effort

Sheet 10: System States

















































System State System Behaviour

State Transitions




S1 OFF System draws minimum power from the vehicle battery ( <xx mA)

Present State Condition Future State




System waits for receiving the wake up signal (Ignition or CAN communication)

S1 OFF C1 S2 Initialization




System has no communication with the vehicle

S1 OFF C9 S1 OFF




S2 Initialization System recieves the wake up signal (Ignition or CAN communication)

S2 Initialization C2 S3 Enable




System draws power from the vehicle battery

S2 Initialization C5 S4 Disable




System performs hardware power up

S2 Initialization C7 S1 OFF




System communicates with the vehicle

S2 Initialization C10 S2 Initialization




S3 Enable System draws power supply from the vehicle battery

S3 Enable C3 S4 Disable




System assists in reducing the steering effort

S3 Enable C8 S1 OFF




System assists in damping undesirable forces acting on the steering system

S3 Enable C11 S3 Enable




System assists by executing vehicle commands

S4 Disable C4 S1 OFF




System assists in both reducing the steering effort and also executes vehicle commands at the sametime

S4 Disable C6 S2 Initialization






System assists for Start/Stop (MSA) features

S4 Disable C12 S4 Disable
Sx System states



System communicates with the vehicle




Cx Conditions for transitioning from one state to the other



S4 Disable System draws power supply from the vehicle battery










System does not provide assist










System communicates with the vehicle




Categories of Faults








Fault Definition Response Type








F1 Immideate shutdown fault * Most severe type of response
* Immediate removal of assist
* Competent control of the motor cannot be assured		 Safety Critical

Conditions for Transitions



F2 Controlled shutdown fault (Faults in the torque path) * The torque path is disconnected from the operator and the motor is commutated with the motor velocity command
* Output is ramped out as a function of motor velocity and time		 Safety Critical

C1 Reception of wake up signal (Ignition or CAN communication)




F3 Information only fault (Performance or information only related faults) * System continues to operate and certain features are disabled or operated in a reduced performance mode Non-safety Critical

C2 Continued reception of wake up signal (Ignition or CAN communication) AND



Rest Time based shutdown (Indexed Ramp) * System ramps out assist as a function of time Safety Critical

System hardware power up complete AND









No fault identified (OR) Fault identified is non-safety critical

Safety critical fault identified










C4 No wake up signal (Ignition or CAN communication) OR









Reception of a request for immediate transition to OFF

Safety critical fault identified










C6 Continued reception of wake up signal (Ignition or CAN communication) AND









Recovery from safety critical fault AND









No fault identified (OR) Fault identified is non-safety critical

No wake up signal (Ignition or CAN communication)
